#* {{quote-book|author=Albert Schwegler|authorlink=Albert Schwegler|chapter=Christianity and Scholasticism|translator={{w|James Hutchison Stirling}}|title=Handbook of the History of Philosophy{{nb...|Translated and Annotated [...]}}|location=Edinburgh|publisher=Edmonston & Douglas|year=1867|pages=142–143|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=FZECAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA143|oclc=897483774|passage=The Neo Platonic philosophy, it will now be seen, is monism, and the completion, consequently, of ancient philosophy, so far as it would reduce the totality of being to a single ultimate ground. As able, however, to find its highest principle, from which all the rest are derived, not through self-consciousness and natural rational explanation, but only through ecstasy, mystic annihilation of self, '''ascesis''', theurgy, it is a desperate overleaping of all—and, consequently, the self-destruction of ancient—philosophy.|lang=en}}
#* {{quote-journal|author=A[rthur] H[ilary] Armstrong|authorlink=A. H. Armstrong|title=Platonic Mysticism|editor=T. S. Gregory|journal=[[w:Dublin Review (Catholic periodical)|The Dublin Review]]|location=Birmingham; Dublin|publisher=[[w:Burns & Oates|Burns Oates & Washbourne]]{{nb...|5 Norfolk Road, Edgbaston, Birmingham; 28 Ashley Place, S.W.1; and 21/22 D’Olier Street, Dublin}}|month=April|year=1945|volume=216|issue=433|page=133|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ozoYAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA2-PP147|oclc=320505649|passage=This intellectual discipline, this progressive unification and concentration of the mind is an important part of the preparatory '''ascesis''', the work of purification which must be carried through before any approach towards the mystical union can be expected.|lang=en}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Joost A[braham] M[aurits] Meerloo|authorlink=Joost Meerloo|chapter=Totalitaria and Its Dictatorship|title=The Rape of the Mind: The Psychology of Thought Control, Menticide, and Brainwashing|location=Cleveland, Oh.; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:World Publishing Company|The World Publishing Company]]|year=1956|page=109|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=NZd9AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA109|oclc=781951098|passage=The happiness of the Oriental psyche lies in the ecstasy of feeling united with the universal cosmos. '''Ascesis''', self-redemption, and poverty are better realized ideals in Oriental culture than in our Western society.|lang=en}}
